Gradlerio looks for 7 addresses in parallel, the 6 defined below and the 7th is the address the DS is connected to. Any network drives you have should be irrelevant. It uses whichever one connects first.

public void setTeam(int team) {

this.team = team;

setAddresses(

"roborio-" + team + "-FRC.local", // Default mDNS

"10." + (team / 100) + "." + (team % 100) + ".2", // 10.TE.AM.2

"172.22.11.2", // USB

// Weird Environments

"roborio-" + team + "-FRC", // Default DNS

"roborio-" + team + "-FRC.lan", // LAN mDNS/DNS

"roborio-" + team + "-FRC.frc-field.local" /// Practice Field mDNS

);

}

In order for it to take 2+ minutes to connect, I’d suspect one or more of the following is true:

There’s a firewall blocking or slowing down the connections

The Driver station isn’t connected

For some reason the radio isn’t giving the roboRIO a 10.TE. AM -2 IP address (this can happen if team number isn’t set)

Something else is interfering with mdns (For example, my home internet provider tries to resolve mDNS externally and takes a long time to time out
